Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics package
- Used npm (the project's package manager) to install @vercel/analytics
- Updated package.json to include the new dependency
- Updated package-lock.json with the new dependency tree

### 2. Added Analytics component to root layout
- Modified app/layout.tsx to import Analytics from '@vercel/analytics/next'
- Added <Analytics /> component inside the <body> tag, after {children} and <SpeedInsights />
- Preserved all existing code structure and formatting

### 3. Configured ESLint
- Created .eslintrc.json with strict configuration for the project
- This was necessary to run the linter as requested

### 4. Verified the implementation
- Build completed successfully with no errors
- Linter passed with no warnings or errors
- All changes follow Next.js App Router best practices

## Files Modified
- app/layout.tsx - Added Analytics import and component
- package.json - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- package-lock.json - Updated with new dependency tree
- .eslintrc.json - Created ESLint configuration (new file)

## Implementation Details
The project uses Next.js 15 with the App Router (app directory), so the Analytics component was added to the root layout file (app/layout.tsx). The component is placed inside the <body> tag after the existing <SpeedInsights /> component, following the recommended pattern for Vercel analytics.

All changes preserve the existing code structure and follow the project's coding conventions. The implementation is ready for deployment to Vercel, where the analytics will automatically start tracking page views and web vitals.
